Aligning language models with human preferences requires knowing what humans actually prefer — and this is harder than it sounds. Existing approaches to preference learning treat the problem as one of aggregation: collect pairwise comparisons, fit a reward model, and optimize against it. The implicit assumption is that human preferences are stable latent quantities waiting to be measured. But preferences are frequently context-sensitive, inconsistent across elicitation methods, and systematically distorted by framing effects that no reward model trained on surface-level comparisons can detect. Without a mechanism for identifying when preference signals are structurally unreliable, optimization pressure amplifies noise as readily as it amplifies signal. The mechanism we introduce addresses precisely this gap: rather than treating all preference data as equally informative, it assigns reliability estimates to individual comparisons based on internal consistency structure, ensuring that the reward model is shaped by the subset of preference data that is coherent enough to be trusted.

DRAFT B (generic):
Existing approaches to preference learning and alignment have made substantial progress by treating human feedback as a stable signal to be aggregated, optimized, or distilled into reward models. Yet this framing systematically obscures a deeper problem: human preferences are not simply noisy measurements of some underlying utility function, but contextually sensitive, revisable, and sometimes mutually inconsistent across individuals and timeframes. Methods grounded in RLHF, constitutional AI, and inverse reward design each inherit this assumption in different ways, producing systems that are responsive to expressed preferences without being genuinely accountable to them. The mechanism we develop here addresses precisely this gap.

DRAFT C (original preference):
